Outcomes Measured for Students
Recovery High School programs serve a complex population of students that require a
specialized approach to balance students’ unique academic and therapeutic
programming needs. These programs enroll a significantly higher number of students with
disabilities, and those who are considered low-income and high needs, as compared to
state averages for those identities. Those factors, combined with the inherent issues of a
school composed of students diagnosed with a substance use disorder, create particular
challenges to addressing each student’s needs. Recovery High School programs support
these individual needs by developing and following an individualized recovery plan while
providing a comprehensive four-year high school education that supports students to
reach success in their academic and personal lives.
